Introduction¶

This Assignment was to collect a dataset from one or more open web API's and to process and analyse the data.

We used two different APIs to obtain data, namely a Newspaper API obviously called NewsAPI (https://newsapi.org/) and the Elsevier Research API

Our overarching goal was to compare the difference in readability levels between research papers and newspapers. And to compare between subsets, namely broadsheet vs tabloid and science research papers vs arts research papers.

We also included some analysis on individual authors to see if there was any correlation between different paper metrics, ie number of citations, age of paper, type of paper, readability of paper. This should have been possible directly with the Elsevier API as well as being able to pull papers from particular institutions however this functionality seems to be broken. Until this was fixed we had to manually access each authors academic profile on Elsevier using their scopus ID and download a CSV of their publications. This was then processed to pull paper ID's and Elsevier API was used to pull the paper details.

Upon inspection it was realised using a web scraper such as Beautiful Soup to download the Author CSV was not possible as Elsevier employs a massive amount of embedded Javascript to prevent people doing this. One way to automate this would have been to use a web driver interface such as Selenium which employs a full internet browser and can emulate button clicks etc. However this was deemed outside the scope for this project.

Process¶

Tackling this as a team we split the project into two parts the NewsAPI and the Research Paper API.

To make the process more clear we seperated the process into four steps

  • Collect the data: pull the information from the API's, basic preprocessing was performed to reduce the overall size of the data.
  • Clean the data: remove irrelevant or incomplete data that may skew the results. Also setup the data in a structure that it would be easy to analyse
  • Analyse the data: create any new metrics for quantifying what we want to analyse, ie readabiliy, age etc
  • Visualise the data: take the analysed data and display it in a human readable format and derive conclusions from what we observe.

Collect Data¶

Pull the information from the API's, basic preprocessing was performed to reduce the overall size of the data.

Research Paper Data¶

While collecting the data we decided to only use the abstracts of the papers as the data in the paper body included all the formatting for the paper such as tables, figures etc. Hence we will assume the abstract is indicative of the rest of the paper.

To compare different faculties it was not actually possible to search by category defined by the author. Instead we used the categories defined by science direct as searchterms.

Note: the collect data steps of this assignment have been commented out as it takes a long time to collect all the data. JSON files are provided that will load in the data for the Clean Data stage. The collect data stage takes about an hour to pull 5000 search results for each searchterm and then pull 1000 papers details from each searchterm once multiprocessing was implemented

getSearchResultsEls()¶

In [2]:
def getSearchResultsEls(searchterm, OUTPUT=True):
    '''Takes a searchterm as a string and queries the scopus database
    returns a list of tuples of the form (list of results(dict), searchterm)'''
    
    if OUTPUT:
        print("Starting search for: {}".format(searchterm,))
    
    ## Initialize doc search object and execute search, retrieving all results
    doc_srch = ElsSearch(searchterm,'scopus')
    doc_srch.execute(client, get_all = True)
    
    if OUTPUT:
        print("Successfully searched for: {}, found {} results".format(searchterm, len(doc_srch.results)))
    
    return doc_srch.results, searchterm

Runs all the searches in parallel. IO is limited by server response time, hence we request all the searchresults at the same time

readSearchResult( )¶

In [5]:
def readSearchResult(searchterm, result, silent=True): #function which is passed to map
    '''Extracts paper id from search result, queries scopus for paper details using paper id,
    outputs a dataframe with the columns: 'searchterm', 'title', 'abstract' ''' 
    
    scopus_id = result['link'][0]['@href'][-11:] #specific place scopus id is stored in result\

    try:
        docDetails = pullDocDetails(scopus_id) #returns a dict for the result
        docDetails['searchterm'] = searchterm #add column
        if not silent:
            if len(docDetails['title'])>80:
                print("Successfully read: {}...".format(docDetails['title'][:80]))
            else:
                print("Successfully read: {}".format(docDetails['title']))
        return docDetails

    except TypeError as e: 
        print("Error: {}".format(e))
        return dict()

pullDocDetails()¶

Pull Paper Data by Scopus_id using the Elsevier API and extract the specific info we want

In [6]:
def pullDocDetails(scopus_id, silent = True):

    if type(scopus_id) != str:
        scopus_id = str(scopus_id)

    scp_doc = AbsDoc(scp_id = scopus_id)

    if not scp_doc.read(client):
        raise TypeError("Scopus returned no data for this Document Id")

    doc = dict()
    doc['title']    = scp_doc.data['item']['bibrecord']['head']['citation-title']
    doc['abstract'] = scp_doc.data['item']['bibrecord']['head']['abstracts']
    
    return doc

Implementing Multiprocessing¶

Testing was carried out on the searchterms = ['star+trek+vs+star+wars']; with approx 200 results, to find the optimal amount of processes.

Sending lots of requests to the server at a time resulted in more documents being returned as None. This may be because the server is refusing to serve us results as we are bombarding it. This may also be giving us false results for the higher process counts as these None entries return faster. Hence there was a trade off between speed and accuracy.

  • 16min 10s w/ no multiprocessing
  • 1min 45s w/ 20 processes
  • 1min 49s w/ 50 processes
  • 1min 17s w/ 100 processes, lots of data returned as None
  • 1min 3s w/ 150 processes, lots of data returned as None
  • 1min 5s w/ 200 processes, lots of data returned as None

A happy medium is around 50 processes. Running this on the larger data set returned approximately 5 None results per 1000 papers.

News Data¶

pullArticles()¶

Function to pull articles using the NewsAPI

In [8]:
def pullArticles(sources, numberOfPages):
    
    #check if user inputted integer for number of pages
    if isinstance(numberOfPages, int):
        num_pages = numberOfPages
    else:
        print("Invalid Number of Pages, please enter an integer amount")
        return

    #iterate through list of sources specified by the user
    for source, source_info in sources.items():
        print("Attempting to pull from '{}', info: {} ".format(source,source_info))
        articles[source] = list()
    
        #pull data from NewsAPI
        for page in range(num_pages):
            #print("Page: {}, ".format(page+1), end="")
            data = newsapi.get_everything(q='',
                                          sources=source,
                                          domains=source_info['domain'],
                                          language=source_info['language'],
                                          page=page+1)
            if data['status'] == 'ok':
                #print("Success")
                articles[source].extend(data['articles'])
            else:
                print("Error, discarding pulled data")
                
    return articles

def saveArticles(articles,fname):
    
    fout = open(fname, "w")
    fout.write(json.dumps(articles))
    fout.close()
    print('Save to: {}, Successful'.format(fname))
        
def loadArticles(fname):
    
    fin = open(fname,"r")
    s = fin.read()
    fin.close()
    articles = json.loads(s)
    print('Read from: {}, Successful'.format(fname))
    return articles

pretty_value_counts()¶

Prettifies the output of value_counts()

In [13]:
def pretty_value_counts(data, key):
    vals = data[key].value_counts()
    
    print('-'*5, key.upper(), '-'*5)
    print("Value: \tCount:")
    print("-"*15)
    
    for val, count in vals.items():
        if type(val)==str and len(val)>40:
            print("{}... \t{}".format(val[:40], count))
        else:
            print(val, count, sep="\t")
        
    print("NaN: \t{}".format(len(data)-vals.sum()))
    print("-"*15)
    
    return

Convert to Data Frames¶

In [33]:
def convertToDF(sources, articles):
    totalSource = []
    totalScore = []

    #iterate through sources
    for source, source_info in sources.items():
        listSource = []
        listScore = []
    
        #iterate through articles in each source, and add their Read Score to a list
        for count in range(len(articles[source])):
            x = source_info["name"]
            y = articles[source][count]["Read Score"]
            listSource.append(x)
            listScore.append(y)
    
        setScore = set(listScore)
        listScore = list(setScore) #removed duplicate values
        listSource = listSource[0:len(listScore)] #makes list of sources the same length as list of scores
        
        totalSource.extend(listSource)
        totalScore.extend(listScore)

    #create large data frame with all sources and scores
    ReadabilityScores = pd.DataFrame({"Source":totalSource,
                                      "Score":totalScore
                                     })
    #remove any zero values
    ReadabilityScores = ReadabilityScores[ReadabilityScores['Score'] != 0.0]
    
    return ReadabilityScores
    
#convertToDF(sources, articles)

def seperateDFs(articles, sources):

    #group the big df by Source
    grouped = ReadabilityScores.groupby("Source")

    #create dictionary key = source , value = data frame for that source
    dictionaryDF = {} 

    #iterate through sources and create an individual data frame for each
    for source, source_info in sources.items():
        dictionaryDF[source_info["name"]] = grouped.get_group(source_info["name"])
    
    #return dictionary, individual data frames can be accessed by dictionaryDF["The Irish Times"] etc.
    return dictionaryDF

Analysis¶

Readability Test¶

The majority of our analysis will be based on Readability which is quantified using the Flesch reading-ease test. The Flesch readability tests are designed to indicate how difficult a passage in English is to understand. This test rates text on a 100-point scale. The higher the score, the easier it is to understand the document. For most standard files, you want the score to be between 60 and 70.

The formula for the Flesch reading-ease score (FRES) test is:

\begin{align} =& 206.835 - 1.015 \left( \text{ASL} \right) - 84.6 \left( \text{ASW} \right) \\ =& 206.835 - 1.015 \left( \frac{\text{total words}} {\text{total sentences}} \right) - 84.6 \left( \frac{\text{total syllables}} {\text{total words}} \right) \end{align}

where:

  • ASL = average sentence length (the number of words divided by the number of sentences)

  • ASW = average number of syllables per word (the number of syllables divided by the number of words)

Score Notes
90-100 Very easy to read. Easily understood by an average 11-year-old student.
80-90 Easy to read. Conversational English for consumers.
70-80 Fairly easy to read.
60-70 Plain English. Easily understood by 13- to 15-year-old students.
50-60 Fairly difficult to read.
30-50 Difficult to read.
0-30 Very difficult to read. Best understood by university graduates.

For our analysis we assume that the abstract of the document is indicative of its overall complexity.

fleschScore()¶

Employs the flesch score test and returns a float value quantifying its readability and a NaN value if an error occurs

In [35]:
def fleschScore(text, ret_errors = False, OUTPUT = False):
    if text == None :
        return np.NaN

    text_parsed = parseText(text, NewsAPI=True, OUTPUT = OUTPUT)

    NOSy = 0 #Number of syllables in the text
    NOW = 0 #Number of words in the text
    NOS = len(text_parsed) #Number of sentences in the text

    if NOS == 0:
        return np.NaN

    errors = 0

    for sentence in text_parsed:
        NOW += len(sentence) #Number of words in the sentence

        for word in sentence:
            try:
                NOSy += nsyl(word)

            except Exception as e:
                #print(e)
                errors += 1
                if OUTPUT:
                    print("Error processing: \"{}\"".format(word))
                try: #if word not found in cmudict use approximation
                    NOSy += syllables(word)

                except Exception as e: #if string is invalid (a number, symbol, etc)
                    print("Error counting syllables in: \"{}\"".format(word))
                    #print(e)

    ASL = NOW / NOS
    ASW = NOSy / NOW
    RS = 206.835 - (1.015 * ASL) - (84.6 * ASW)

    # if RS <= 0:
    #     return np.NaN
    # if RS >= 100:
    #     return np.NaN
    if ret_errors:
        return (RS, errors)
    if OUTPUT:
        print(RS)
    return RS

parseText()¶

Returns a list of lists where its a list of sentences containing lists of words.

In [36]:
def parseText(text, NewsAPI=False, OUTPUT = False):

    #split the text into sentences
    tokenizer = nltk.data.load('tokenizers/punkt/english.pickle')
    sentences = tokenizer.tokenize(text)

    #split the sentences into words
    sentences = [re.compile('\w+').findall(sentence) for sentence in sentences]

    #The last sentence of the NewsAPI text can't be used because of the presence of [+1210 chars]
    #therefore it must be removed
#     if NewsAPI: #checks if text is from NewsAPI or Academic Paper
#         if OUTPUT:
#             print("Removing: \"{}\" ".format(sentences[-1]))
#         del(sentences[-1])

    return sentences

def doctype_id(doc_string):
    if doc_string == 'Article':
        return 7
    if doc_string == 'Conference Paper':
        return 6
    if doc_string == 'Review':
        return 5 
    if doc_string == 'Editorial':
        return 4
    if doc_string == 'Book Chapter':
        return 3
    if doc_string == 'Note':
        return 2
    if doc_string == 'Erratum':
        return 1
    if doc_string == 'NaN: ':
        return 0
    
author_data['DocType Id'] = [doctype_id(doc_type) for doc_type in author_data['Document Type']]

News Data¶

Analyse a news source and create a new column with the readability scores

In [40]:
def assignFleschScore(sources, articles):
    
    #iterate through sources
    for source, source_info in sources.items():
        
        #iterate through articles in each source to assign each a score
        for count in range(len(articles[source])):
        
            #print("Checking search result no: {}, ".format(count),end="")
            test_text = articles[source][count]["content"]
            score = fleschScore(test_text)
            articles[source][count]["Read Score"] = score
            #print("{}".format(score))
    return articles

plot_author_statsvstime()¶

In [49]:
def plot_author_statsvstime(author_data, author):
    
    grouped_author = author_data.groupby('Author').get_group(author)
    grouped_year = grouped_author.groupby('Year')
    readability_binned = grouped_year['Readability'].agg(np.mean)
    citations_binned = grouped_year['Cited by'].agg(np.mean)

  
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(18,6))
    
    most_cited_paper = author_data.iloc[author_data['Cited by'].idxmax()]
    
    host = fig.add_subplot(122) #define the main plot
    par1 = host.twinx() #add a parasite plot

    fig.suptitle('{} stats vs time'.format(author))
    host.set_xlabel("Year Published")
    host.set_ylabel("Readability")
    par1.set_ylabel("Citations")

    color1 = plt.cm.viridis(0.5)
    color2 = plt.cm.viridis(0.9)

    p1, = host.plot(readability_binned, color=color1, label="Readability")
    p2, = par1.plot(citations_binned, color=color2, label="Citations")

    lns = [p1, p2]
    host.legend(handles=lns, loc='best')  
      
    host.autoscale(enable=True, axis='x', tight=True)
    par1.autoscale(enable=True, axis='x', tight=True)
    
    if fig == None:
        plt.show()

pi_subplot()¶

In [50]:
def pi_subplot(figure, counts, title, i, legend = False, num_x = 3, num_y = 1):
    
    ax = figure.add_subplot(num_y,num_x,i)
       
    if legend:
        counts.plot(kind='pie', ax=ax, autopct='%2.0f%%', startangle=180, fontsize=12, counterclock=False, labels=None)
        ax.legend(loc="right", labels=counts.index)

    else:    
        counts.plot(kind='pie', ax=ax, autopct='%2.0f%%', startangle=180, fontsize=12, counterclock=False)

    ax.set_xlabel('')
    ax.set_ylabel('')
    
    ax.set_title(title, fontsize=16)

Author_stats()¶

In [51]:
def Author_stats(author_data, author): 
    '''Display a bunch of stats about an author'''
    
    # variation of published documents type, readability and citations over time
    plot_author_statsvstime(author_data, author)
    
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(18,6))
    fig.suptitle('Document stat Distribution',fontsize = 20)
    
    #Document Type Distribution
    doc_counts = pd.value_counts(author_data['Document Type'])
    pi_subplot(fig, doc_counts, "Document Type Distribution", 1, legend=True)

    #Readability Distribution
    bins = [i for i in np.arange(0,60,10)]+[100]

    binned = pd.cut(author_data['Readability'], bins)
    read_counts = pd.value_counts(binned)
    read_counts.sort_index(inplace=True)
    
    pi_subplot(fig, read_counts, "Readability Distribution", 2)
    
    #Citation Distribution
    bins = [0,1,2]
    bins += [i for i in range(5,25,10)]
    bins += [i for i in range(30,100,30)]
    max_val = int(author_data['Cited by'].max())
    bins += [max_val]

    binned = pd.cut(author_data['Cited by'], bins)
    citation_counts = pd.value_counts(binned)
    citation_counts.sort_index(inplace=True)
    
    pi_subplot(fig, citation_counts, "Citation Distribution", 3)
    plt.show()
    
    #Correlation Matrix
    correlation_data = author_data[['Cited by', 'Readability', 'Age', 'DocType Id']]
    correlation_data = correlation_data[author_data['Cited by'] < 100]
    
    axes = pd.plotting.scatter_matrix(correlation_data, alpha=0.2, figsize = (18,18))
    pl.suptitle('Correlation Matrix', fontsize = 20)
    
author = 'John T. Sheridan'    
Author_stats(author_data, author)

Stats vs Time¶

The readability of John T. Sheridans (a lecturer in the school of Electronic Engineering and James thesis supervisor) research papers varies over time. The average readability score fluctuates between 5 and 30 between the years of 1990 and 2018. There is no discernible pattern to be seen between the average readability of the research papers published and the number of years spent working as a researcher.

Stat Distribution¶

The citations of John T. Sheridans research papers vary between 0 and 70 between the years of 1990 and 2018. There is no discernible pattern to be observed between the number of citations and the year of publishing. The one exception to this rule is that between the years 2000-2004 there was a spike in the average number of citations per research paper. This leads us to conclude that John T. Sheridan must have been completing exciting and novel research at this point.

There is no discernible correlation between average readability of articles in a year and number of citations in a year.

Correlation Matrix¶

The correlation matrix shows no clear correlations between any two sets of data available. This result was surprising. We expected that the age of the article might be correlated with the number of citations. We also expected that the readability might be correlated with the number of citations, but neither of these expectations were true.
